panels.description:
Shows how many of new time-series are created every second.  High churn rate tightly connected with database performance and may result in unexpected OOM's or slow queries. It is recommended to always keep an eye on this metric to avoid unexpected cardinality "explosions".

Good references to read:
* https://www.robustperception.io/cardinality-is-key
* https://www.robustperception.io/using-tsdb-analyze-to-investigate-churn-and-cardinality
panels.title: Churn Rate

panels.description:
The total space needed to store all the datapoints during the selected retention given the current ingestion rate, the average of dedup points on the selected period and the average size of one datapoint.

projected size = (ingestion rate - avg rate of dedup for $__range) * avg size one of datapoint * selected retention
panels.title: vmstorage - Projected Total Disk Usage

panels.description:
The total space needed to store all the datapoints during the selected retention given the current ingestion rate, the average of dedup points on the selected period and the average size of one datapoint.

projected size per vmstorage = ( (ingestion rate - avg rate of dedup for $__range) * avg size one of datapoint * selected retention ) / nb of vmstorage
panels.title: vmstorage - Disk Space needed per vmstorage

panels.description:
The recommended total amount of RAM for all the vmstorage instances can be calculated from the number of active time series:
RAM = active_time_series * 1KB.

Time series is active if it received at least a single data point during the last hour or if it has been queried during the last hour.
panels.title: vmstorage - Total RAM required for optimal performance

panels.description:
The recommended total amount of RAM for all the vmstorage instances can be calculated from the number of active time series: RAM = active_time_series * 1KB.

Time series is active if it received at least a single data point during the last hour or if it has been queried during the last hour.

Unused RAM = allowed RAM - cache - needed RAM for active TS
panels.title: vmstorage - Total Unused RAM

panels.description:
* `*` - unsupported query path
* `/write` - insert into VM
* `/metrics` - query VM system metrics
* `/query` - query instant values
* `/query_range` - query over a range of time
* `/series` - match a certain label set
* `/label/{}/values` - query a list of label values (variables mostly)
panels.title: vminsert - Requests Rate

panels.description:
Shows how many ongoing insertions are taking place.
* `max` - equal to number of CPU * 4 by default. May be configured with `maxConcurrentInserts` flag
* `current` - current number of goroutines busy with processing requests

When `current` hits `max` constantly, it means vminsert node is overloaded and require more CPU or higher limits.
panels.title: vminsert - Concurrent Inserts

panels.description: Shows how many rows per second every storage node accepts. This metric doesn't show all stored rows since some of them may be dropped because of wrong timestamps or decode errors.
panels.title: vmstorage - Ingestion Rate

panels.description: How many datapoints are in RAM queue waiting to be written into storage. The number of pending data points should be in the range from 0 to `2*<ingestion_rate>`, since VictoriaMetrics pushes pending data to persistent storage every second. The index datapoints value in general is much lower.
panels.title: vmstorage - Pending Datapoints

panels.description:
Shows how many ongoing insertions are taking place.
* `max` - equal to number of CPU * 2
* `current` - current number of goroutines busy with inserting rows into storage

When `current` hits `max` constantly, it means storage is overloaded and require more CPU.
panels.title: vmstorage - Concurrent Inserts

panels.description:
Data parts of LSM tree.
High number of parts could be an evidence of slow merge performance - check the resource utilization.
* `indexdb` - inverted index
* `storage/small` - recently added parts of data ingested into storage(hot data)
* `storage/big` -  small parts gradually merged into big parts (cold data)
panels.title: vmstorage - LSM parts

panels.description: The number of on-going merges in storage nodes.  It is expected to have high numbers for `storage/small` metric.
panels.title: vmstorage - Active Merges

panels.description: The number of rows merged per second by storage nodes.
panels.title: vmstorage - Merge Speed

panels.description: Shows amount of on-disk space occupied by data (datapoints & indexes) and caches.
panels.title: vmstorage - Disk Space Usage

panels.description:
Removed superflouos samples from time series if they are located closer to each other than the dedup duration. Keep in mind that dedup on the storage is only performed during merge (aka delayed).

See the `-dedup.minScrapeInterval` flag.
panels.title: vmstorage - Deduplicated Samples Rate

panels.description: zstd compression ratio
panels.title: vmstorage - Compression Ratio

panels.description: Request rate accepted by vmselect nodes
panels.title: vmselect - Requests Rate

panels.description: Number of queries that have exceeded the -search.logSlowQueryDuration value of vmselect nodes
panels.title: vmselect - Slow Queries

panels.description:
Shows how many ongoing insertions are taking place.
* `max` - equal to number of CPU * 2 by default. May be configured with `search.maxConcurrentRequests` flag
* `current` - current number of goroutines busy with processing requests

When `current` hits `max` constantly, it means vmselect node is overloaded and require more CPU or higher limits.
panels.title: vmselect - Concurrent Selects

panels.description:
Removed superflouos samples from time series if they are located closer to each other than the dedup duration. As dedup on storage is performed during merge, vmselect dedup points that have not been deduplicated yet by the storage.

See the `-dedup.minScrapeInterval` flag.
panels.title: vmselect - Deduplicated Samples Rate
